# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: device-orientation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] An **accelerometer** is a device that measures the proper acceleration of an object.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Proper acceleration is the acceleration (the rate of change of velocity) of the object relative to an observer who is in free fall (that is, relative to an inertial frame of reference).
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Proper acceleration is different from coordinate acceleration, which is acceleration with respect to a given coordinate system, which may or may not be accelerating.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] For example, an accelerometer at rest on the surface of the Earth will measure an acceleration due to Earth's gravity straight upwards of about *g* ≈ 9.81 m/s2.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] By contrast, an accelerometer that is in free fall will measure zero acceleration.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Highly sensitive accelerometers are used in inertial navigation systems for aircraft and missiles.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] In unmanned aerial vehicles, accelerometers help to stabilize flight.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Micromachined micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS) accelerometers are used in handheld electronic devices such as smartphones, cameras and video-game controllers to detect movement and orientation of these devices.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Vibration in industrial machinery is monitored by accelerometers.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Seismometers are sensitive accelerometers for monitoring ground movement such as earthquakes.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] When two or more accelerometers are coordinated with one another, they can measure differences in proper acceleration, particularly gravity, over their separation in space—that is, the gradient of the gravitational field.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Gravity gradiometry is useful because absolute gravity is a weak effect and depends on the local density of the Earth, which is quite variable.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] A single-axis accelerometer measures acceleration along a specified axis.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] A multi-axis accelerometer detects both the magnitude and the direction of the proper acceleration, as a vector quantity, and is usually implemented as several single-axis accelerometers oriented along different axes.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] An accelerometer measures proper acceleration, which is the acceleration it experiences relative to freefall and is the acceleration felt by people and objects.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Put another way, at any point in spacetime the equivalence principle guarantees the existence of a local inertial frame, and an accelerometer measures the acceleration relative to that frame.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Such accelerations are popularly denoted g-force; i.e., in comparison to standard gravity.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] An accelerometer at rest relative to the Earth's surface will indicate approximately 1 g *upwards* because the Earth's surface exerts a normal force upwards relative to the local inertial frame (the frame of a freely falling object near the surface).
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] To obtain the acceleration due to motion with respect to the Earth, this "gravity offset" must be subtracted and corrections made for effects caused by the Earth's rotation relative to the inertial frame.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] The reason for the appearance of a gravitational offset is Einstein's equivalence principle, which states that the effects of gravity on an object are indistinguishable from acceleration.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] When held fixed in a gravitational field by, for example, applying a ground reaction force or an equivalent upward thrust, the reference frame for an accelerometer (its own casing) accelerates upwards with respect to a free-falling reference frame.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] For similar reasons, an accelerometer will read *zero* during any type of free fall.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] This includes use in a coasting spaceship in deep space far from any mass, a spaceship orbiting the Earth, an airplane in a parabolic "zero-g" arc, or any free-fall in a vacuum.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Another example is free-fall at a sufficiently high altitude that atmospheric effects can be neglected.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] However, this does not include a (non-free) fall in which air resistance produces drag forces that reduce the acceleration until constant terminal velocity is reached.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] At terminal velocity, the accelerometer will indicate 1 g acceleration upwards.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] For the same reason a skydiver, upon reaching terminal velocity, does not feel as though he or she were in "free-fall", but rather experiences a feeling similar to being supported (at 1 g) on a "bed" of uprushing air.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Acceleration is quantified in the SI unit metres per second per second (m/s2), in the cgs unit gal (Gal), or popularly in terms of standard gravity (*g*).
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] For the practical purpose of finding the acceleration of objects with respect to the Earth, such as for use in an inertial navigation system, a knowledge of local gravity is required.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] This can be obtained either by calibrating the device at rest, or from a known model of gravity at the approximate current position.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] A basic mechanical accelerometer is a damped proof mass on a spring.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] When the accelerometer experiences an acceleration, Newton's third law causes the spring's compression (or extension) to adjust to exert an equivalent force on the mass to counteract the acceleration.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Since the spring's force scales linearly with the length change (according to Hooke's law) and because the spring constant and mass are known constants, a measurement of the spring's compression (or extension) is also a measurement of acceleration.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] The system is damped to prevent oscillations of the mass and spring interfering with measurements.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] However, the damping causes accelerometers to have a frequency response.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Many animals have sensory organs to detect acceleration, especially gravity.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] In these, the proof mass is usually one or more crystals of calcium carbonate otoliths (Latin for "ear stone") or statoconia, acting against a bed of hairs connected to neurons.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] The hairs form the springs, with the neurons as sensors.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Many vertebrates, including humans, have these structures in their inner ears.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Most invertebrates have similar organs, but not as part of their hearing organs.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Mechanical accelerometers are often designed so that an electronic circuit senses a small amount of motion, then pushes on the proof mass with some type of linear motor to keep the proof mass from moving far.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] The motor might be an electromagnet or in very small accelerometers, electrostatic.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Since the circuit's electronic behavior can be carefully designed, and the proof mass does not move far, these designs can be very stable (i.e. they do not oscillate), very linear with a controlled frequency response.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] In mechanical accelerometers, measurement is often electrical, piezoelectric, piezoresistive or capacitive.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Piezoelectric accelerometers use piezoceramic sensors (e.g. lead zirconate titanate) or single crystals (e.g. quartz, tourmaline).
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] They are unmatched in high frequency measurements, low packaged weight, and resistance to high temperatures.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Piezoresistive accelerometers resist shock (very high accelerations) better.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Capacitive accelerometers typically use a silicon micro-machined sensing element.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Modern mechanical accelerometers are often small *micro-electro-mechanical systems* (MEMS), and are often very simple MEMS devices, consisting of little more than a cantilever beam with a proof mass (also known as *seismic mass*).
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Damping results from the residual gas sealed in the device.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] As long as the Q-factor is not too low, damping does not result in a lower sensitivity.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Under the influence of external accelerations, the proof mass deflects from its neutral position.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] This deflection is measured in an analog or digital manner.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Most commonly, the capacitance between a set of fixed beams and a set of beams attached to the proof mass is measured.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] This method is simple, reliable, and inexpensive.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Integrating piezoresistors in the springs to detect spring deformation, and thus deflection, is a good alternative, although a few more process steps are needed during the fabrication sequence.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] For very high sensitivities quantum tunnelling is also used; this requires a dedicated process making it very expensive.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Optical measurement has been demonstrated in laboratory devices.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Another MEMS-based accelerometer is a thermal (or convective) accelerometer.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] It contains a small heater in a very small dome.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] This heats the air or other fluid inside the dome.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] The thermal bubble acts as the proof mass.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] An accompanying temperature sensor (like a thermistor; or thermopile) in the dome measures the temperature in one location of the dome.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] This measures the location of the heated bubble within the dome.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] When the dome is accelerated, the colder, higher density fluid pushes the heated bubble.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] The temperature measurement is interpreted as acceleration.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Gravity acting on the fluid provides the spring.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Since the proof mass is very lightweight gas, and not held by a beam or lever, thermal accelerometers can survive high shocks.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Another variation uses a wire to both heat the gas and detect the change in temperature.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] The change of temperature changes the resistance of the wire.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] A two dimensional accelerometer can be economically constructed with one dome, one bubble and two measurement devices.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Most micromechanical accelerometers operate *in-plane*, that is, they are designed to be sensitive only to a direction in the plane of the die.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] By integrating two devices perpendicularly on a single die a two-axis accelerometer can be made.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] By adding another *out-of-plane* device, three axes can be measured.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Such a combination may have much lower misalignment error than three discrete models combined after packaging.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Micromechanical accelerometers are available in a wide variety of measuring ranges, reaching up to thousands of *g*'s.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] The designer must compromise between sensitivity and the maximum acceleration that can be measured.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Accelerometers can be used to measure vehicle acceleration.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Accelerometers can be used to measure vibration on cars, machines, buildings, process control systems and safety installations.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] They can also be used to measure seismic activity, inclination, machine vibration, dynamic distance and speed with or without the influence of gravity.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Applications for accelerometers that measure gravity, wherein an accelerometer is specifically configured for use in gravimetry, are called gravimeters.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also increasingly used in the biological sciences.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] High frequency recordings of bi-axial or tri-axial acceleration allows the discrimination of behavioral patterns while animals are out of sight.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] For example, accelerometers have been used to study flight energy expenditure of Harris's Hawk (*Parabuteo unicinctus*).
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Researchers are also using smartphone accelerometers to collect and extract mechano-biological descriptors of resistance exercise.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Increasingly, researchers are deploying accelerometers with additional technology, such as cameras or microphones, to better understand animal behaviour in the wild (for example, hunting behaviour of Canada lynx).
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also used for machinery health monitoring to report the vibration and its changes in time of shafts at the bearings of rotating equipment such as turbines, pumps, fans, rollers, compressors, or bearing fault which, if not attended to promptly, can lead to costly repairs.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Accelerometer vibration data allows the user to monitor machines and detect these faults before the rotating equipment fails completely.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Accelerometers are widely used in structural health monitoring (SHM) of buildings, bridges and other civil infrastructure to record the dynamic response under ambient and forced loads (e.g., wind, traffic, machinery and earthquakes).
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] From these vibration records, engineers estimate modal properties—natural frequencies, damping ratios and mode shapes—often using operational modal analysis (OMA) techniques for in-service structures.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] These parameters are trended over time for condition assessment and model updating.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] In seismic regions, arrays of accelerometers installed in buildings and other structures provide strong-motion data for rapid post-event assessments and long-term performance studies.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Geological Survey's National Strong-Motion Project (NSMP) operates structural arrays and distributes building and structural records via the Center for Engineering Strong Motion Data (CESMD).
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Instrumentation and data-quality practices for building vibration measurements are guided by international standards.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] ISO 4866 provides principles for measuring the vibration of fixed structures and evaluating vibration effects based on structural response, while ISO 10137 gives serviceability recommendations for buildings and walkways with respect to human perception, contents and the structure itself.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Choice of accelerometer technology depends on frequency range and amplitude.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Piezoelectric accelerometers are common for higher-frequency, higher-amplitude measurements, whereas low-noise MEMS accelerometers have become attractive for low-frequency building and bridge monitoring and for dense or wireless deployments due to cost and power advantages.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Recent evaluations and developments show that appropriately selected MEMS devices can identify modal parameters with acceptable accuracy for SHM and have been integrated into high-sensitivity wireless nodes.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Networked and wireless smart-sensor approaches allow distributed monitoring at scale.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Reviews document the shift from wired to wireless SHM systems and the maturation of wireless smart-sensor networks for tasks such as ambient-vibration modal identification and continuous trending.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Accelerometers are often fused with other sensors to improve displacement and drift estimation, especially for large or flexible structures.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] GNSS provides quasi-static and very-low-frequency motion that complements accelerometer-based dynamics; recent studies report accurate dynamic displacement retrieval using high-rate or multi-GNSS solutions combined with accelerometers.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Beyond permanently instrumented assets, indirect and crowdsourced approaches using smartphone accelerometers have been explored, particularly for bridges.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Research has shown that modal frequencies—and in some cases spatial vibration characteristics—can be estimated from accelerometer data collected by vehicles crossing bridges, offering a complementary, low-cost screening tool for large inventories.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Related work has also evaluated smartphone-based ambient vibration monitoring of buildings.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Long-term case studies illustrate large-scale deployments.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Hong Kong's Wind and Structural Health Monitoring System (WASHMS) has instrumented the Tsing Ma Bridge since 1997; subsequent publications report decades of monitoring for load and response in service.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Scotland's Queensferry Crossing was equipped with a comprehensive SHM system including thousands of sensors, and Sydney Harbour Bridge has been reported as instrumented with thousands of sensors for real-time monitoring.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] SHM data are used for continuous condition tracking, event-triggered assessments (e.g., after earthquakes), and to support asset management decisions.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] In bridge engineering, guidance from transportation agencies describes how field data—including accelerometer measurements—can be integrated with inspection and nondestructive evaluation to improve load-rating reliability and maintenance planning.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Zoll's AED Plus uses CPR-D•padz which contain an accelerometer to measure the depth of CPR chest compressions.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Within the last several years, several companies have produced and marketed sports watches for runners that include footpods, containing accelerometers to help determine the speed and distance for the runner wearing the unit.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] In Belgium, accelerometer-based step counters are promoted by the government to encourage people to walk a few thousand steps each day.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Herman Digital Trainer uses accelerometers to measure strike force in physical training.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] It has been suggested to build football helmets with accelerometers in order to measure the impact of head collisions.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] The US Army Research Laboratory developed the Three-Axis Acceleration Switch which has been suggested for this application.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Accelerometers have been used to calculate gait parameters, such as stance and swing phase.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] This kind of sensor can be used to measure or monitor people.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] An inertial navigation system is a navigation aid that uses a computer and motion sensors (accelerometers) to continuously calculate via dead reckoning the position, orientation, and velocity (direction and speed of movement) of a moving object without the need for external references.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Other terms used to refer to inertial navigation systems or closely related devices include inertial guidance system, inertial reference platform, and many other variations.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] An accelerometer alone is unsuitable to determine changes in altitude over distances where the vertical decrease of gravity is significant, such as for aircraft and rockets.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] In the presence of a gravitational gradient, the calibration and data reduction process is numerically unstable.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used to detect apogee in both professional and in amateur rocketry.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also being used in Intelligent Compaction rollers.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used alongside gyroscopes in inertial navigation systems.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] One of the most common uses for MEMS accelerometers is in airbag deployment systems for modern automobiles.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] In this case, the accelerometers are used to detect the rapid negative acceleration of the vehicle to determine when a collision has occurred and the severity of the collision.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Another common automotive use is in electronic stability control systems, which use a lateral accelerometer to measure cornering forces.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] The widespread use of accelerometers in the automotive industry has pushed their cost down dramatically.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Another automotive application is the monitoring of noise, vibration, and harshness (NVH), conditions that cause discomfort for drivers and passengers and may also be indicators of mechanical faults.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Tilting trains use accelerometers and gyroscopes to calculate the required tilt.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Modern electronic accelerometers are used in remote sensing devices intended for the monitoring of active volcanoes to detect the motion of magma.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Accelerometers are increasingly being incorporated into personal electronic devices to detect the orientation of the device, for example, a display screen.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] A *free-fall sensor* (FFS) is an accelerometer used to detect if a system has been dropped and is falling.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] It can then apply safety measures such as parking the head of a hard disk to prevent a head crash and resulting data loss upon impact.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] This device is included in the many common computer and consumer electronic products that are produced by a variety of manufacturers.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] It is also used in some data loggers to monitor handling operations for shipping containers.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] The length of time in free fall is used to calculate the height of drop and to estimate the shock to the package.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Some smartphones, digital audio players and personal digital assistants contain accelerometers for user interface control; often the accelerometer is used to present landscape or portrait views of the device's screen, based on the way the device is being held.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Apple has included an accelerometer in every generation of iPhone, iPad, and iPod touch, as well as in every iPod nano since the 4th generation.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Along with orientation view adjustment, accelerometers in mobile devices can also be used as pedometers, in conjunction with specialized applications.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Automatic Collision Notification (ACN) systems also use accelerometers in a system to call for help in event of a vehicle crash.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Prominent ACN systems include OnStar AACN service, Ford Link's 911 Assist, Toyota's Safety Connect, Lexus Link, or BMW Assist.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Many accelerometer-equipped smartphones also have ACN software available for download.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] ACN systems are activated by detecting crash-strength accelerations.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used in vehicle Electronic stability control systems to measure the vehicle's actual movement.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] A computer compares the vehicle's actual movement to the driver's steering and throttle input.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] The stability control computer can selectively brake individual wheels and/or reduce engine power to minimize the difference between driver input and the vehicle's actual movement.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] This can help prevent the vehicle from spinning or rolling over.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Some pedometers use an accelerometer to more accurately measure the number of steps taken and distance traveled than a mechanical sensor can provide.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Nintendo's Wii video game console uses a controller called a Wii Remote that contains a three-axis accelerometer and was designed primarily for motion input.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Users also have the option of buying an additional motion-sensitive attachment, the Nunchuk, so that motion input could be recorded from both of the user's hands independently.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Is also used on the Nintendo 3DS system.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Sleep phase alarm clocks use accelerometric sensors to detect movement of a sleeper, so that it can wake the person when he/she is not in REM phase, in order to awaken the person more easily.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] A microphone or eardrum is a membrane that responds to oscillations in air pressure.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] These oscillations cause acceleration, so accelerometers can be used to record sound.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] A 2012 study found that voices can be detected in 93% of typical daily situations by accelerometers like those in smartphones fixed to the sternum.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Conversely, carefully designed sounds can cause accelerometers to report false data.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] One study tested 20 models of (MEMS) smartphone accelerometers and found that a majority were susceptible to this attack.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] A number of 21st-century devices use accelerometers to align the screen depending on the direction the device is held (e.g., switching between portrait and landscape modes).
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Such devices include many tablet PCs and some smartphones and digital cameras.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] The Amida Simputer, a handheld Linux device launched in 2004, was the first commercial handheld to have a built-in accelerometer.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] It incorporated many gesture-based interactions using this accelerometer, including page-turning, zoom-in and zoom-out of images, change of portrait to landscape mode, and many simple gesture-based games.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] As of January 2009, almost all new mobile phones and digital cameras contain at least a tilt sensor and sometimes an accelerometer for the purpose of auto image rotation, motion-sensitive mini-games, and correcting shake when taking photographs.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Camcorders use accelerometers for image stabilization, either by moving optical elements to adjust the light path to the sensor to cancel out unintended motions or digitally shifting the image to smooth out detected motion.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Some stills cameras use accelerometers for anti-blur capturing.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] The camera holds off capturing the image when the camera is moving.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] When the camera is still (if only for a millisecond, as could be the case for vibration), the image is captured.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] An example of the application of this technology is the Glogger VS2, a phone application which runs on Symbian based phones with accelerometers such as the Nokia N96.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Some digital cameras contain accelerometers to determine the orientation of the photo being taken and also for rotating the current picture when viewing.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Many laptops feature an accelerometer which is used to detect drops.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] If a drop is detected, the heads of the hard disk are parked to avoid data loss and possible head or disk damage by the ensuing shock.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] A gravimeter, or gravitometer, is an instrument used in gravimetry for measuring the local gravitational field.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] A gravimeter is a type of accelerometer, except that accelerometers are susceptible to all vibrations including noise, that cause oscillatory accelerations.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] This is counteracted in the gravimeter by integral vibration isolation and signal processing.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Though the essential principle of design is the same as in accelerometers, gravimeters are typically designed to be much more sensitive than accelerometers in order to measure very tiny changes within the Earth's gravity, of 1 *g*.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] In contrast, other accelerometers are often designed to measure 1000 *g* or more, and many perform multi-axial measurements.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] The constraints on temporal resolution are usually less for gravimeters, so that resolution can be increased by processing the output with a longer "time constant".
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] If done without a user's knowledge or consent, this is referred to as an inference attack.
[src:device-orientation/accelerometer] Additionally, millions of smartphones could be vulnerable to software cracking via accelerometers.
[src:device-orientation/device-orientation-events] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:device-orientation/device-orientation-events] It’s been available across browsers since September 2023.
[src:device-orientation/device-orientation-events] Device orientation events are events that allow you to detect a device's physical orientation, as well as allowing you to detect the device's motion.
[src:device-orientation/device-orientation-events] Mobile devices commonly have sensors such as gyroscopes, compasses, and accelerometers that can enable applications running on the device to detect the device's orientation and motion.
[src:device-orientation/device-orientation-events] The device orientation events enable you to write web applications that can change their behavior based on the orientation of the user's device, and that can react when the user moves their device.
[src:device-orientation/device-orientation-events] Some user agents require explicit permission before providing access to sensor data.
[src:device-orientation/device-orientation-events] In those environments, `DeviceMotionEvent.requestPermission()` and `DeviceOrientationEvent.requestPermission()` can be used to request this permission from a transient user activation such as a button click.
[src:device-orientation/device-orientation-events] See Requesting permission for more details.
[src:device-orientation/device-orientation-events] Represents changes in the acceleration of a device, as well as the rotation rate.
[src:device-orientation/device-orientation-events] Represents the rate at which the device is rotating around all three axes.
[src:device-orientation/device-orientation-events] Represents changes in the physical orientation of a device.
[src:device-orientation/device-orientation-events] Fired at a regular interval to indicate the amount of physical force of acceleration the device is receiving at that time, and the rate of rotation of the device.
[src:device-orientation/device-orientation-events] Fired when fresh data is available from the device about the current orientation of the device as compared to the Earth coordinate frame.
[src:device-orientation/device-orientation-events] Fired when absolute device orientation changes.
[src:device-orientation/devicemotionevent] The **`DeviceMotionEvent`** interface of the Device Orientation Events provides web developers with information about the speed of changes for the device's position and orientation.
[src:device-orientation/devicemotionevent] Requests the user's permission to access device motion data from the accelerometer and gyroscope sensors.
[src:device-orientation/devicemotionevent] Returns a `Promise` that resolves with a string of `"granted"` or `"denied"`.
[src:device-orientation/devicemotionevent] An object giving the acceleration of the device on the three axis X, Y and Z.
[src:device-orientation/devicemotionevent] An object giving the acceleration of the device on the three axis X, Y and Z with the effect of gravity.
[src:device-orientation/devicemotionevent] An object giving the rate of change of the device's orientation on the three orientation axis alpha, beta and gamma.
[src:device-orientation/devicemotionevent] Rotation rate is expressed in degrees per seconds.
[src:device-orientation/devicemotionevent] A number representing the interval of time, in milliseconds, at which data is obtained from the device.
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientation-event] The **`deviceorientation`** event is fired when fresh data is available from an orientation sensor about the current orientation of the device as compared to the Earth coordinate frame.
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientation-event] This data is gathered from a magnetometer inside the device.
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientation-event] See Orientation and motion data explained for details.
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientation-event] This event is not cancelable and does not bubble.
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientation-event] Use the event name in methods like `addEventListener()`, or set an event handler property.
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientation-event] A boolean that indicates whether the device is providing orientation data absolutely.
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientation-event] A number representing the motion of the device around the z axis, express in degrees with values ranging from 0 (inclusive) to 360 (exclusive).
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientation-event] A number representing the motion of the device around the x axis, expressed in degrees with values ranging from -180 (inclusive) to 180 (exclusive).
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientation-event] This represents the front to back motion of the device.
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientation-event] A number representing the motion of the device around the y axis, expressed in degrees with values ranging from -90 (inclusive) to 90 (exclusive).
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientation-event] This represents the left to right motion of the device.
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientation-event] A number represents the difference between the motion of the device around the z axis of the world system and the direction of the north, expressed in degrees with values ranging from 0 to 360.
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientation-event] The accuracy of the compass given as a positive or negative deviation.
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientationevent] The **`DeviceOrientationEvent`** interface of the Device Orientation Events provides web developers with information from the physical orientation of the device running the web page.
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientationevent] Requests the user's permission to access device orientation data.
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientationevent] A boolean that indicates whether or not the device is providing orientation data absolutely.
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientationevent] A number representing the motion of the device around the x axis, express in degrees with values ranging from -180 (inclusive) to 180 (exclusive).
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientationevent] This represents a front to back motion of the device.
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientationevent] A number representing the motion of the device around the y axis, express in degrees with values ranging from -90 (inclusive) to 90 (exclusive).
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientationevent] This represents a left to right motion of the device.
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientationevent] A number represents the difference between the motion of the device around the z axis of the world system and the direction of the north, express in degrees with values ranging from 0 to 360.
[src:device-orientation/deviceorientationevent] The accuracy of the compass means that the deviation is positive or negative.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] A **gyroscope** (from Ancient Greek γῦρος *gŷros* 'round' and σκοπέω *skopéō* 'to look') is a device used for measuring or maintaining orientation and angular velocity.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] It is a spinning wheel or disc in which the axis of rotation (spin axis) is free to assume any orientation by itself.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] When rotating, the orientation of this axis is unaffected by tilting or rotation of the mounting, due to the conservation of angular momentum.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Gyroscopes based on other operating principles also exist, such as the microchip-packaged MEMS gyroscopes found in electronic devices (sometimes called **gyrometers**), solid-state ring lasers, fibre optic gyroscopes, and the extremely sensitive quantum gyroscope.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Applications of gyroscopes include inertial navigation systems, such as in the Hubble Space Telescope, or inside the steel hull of a submerged submarine.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Due to their precision, gyroscopes are also used in gyrotheodolites to maintain direction in tunnel mining.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Gyroscopes can be used to construct gyrocompasses, which complement or replace magnetic compasses (in ships, aircraft and spacecraft, vehicles in general), to assist in stability (bicycles, motorcycles, and ships; known as **gyrostabilization**) or be used as part of an inertial guidance system.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] MEMS (microelectromechanical system) gyroscopes are popular in some consumer electronics, such as smartphones.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] A gyroscope is an instrument, consisting of a wheel mounted into two or three gimbals providing pivoted supports, for allowing the wheel to rotate about a single axis.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] A set of three gimbals, one mounted on the other with orthogonal pivot axes, may be used to allow a wheel mounted on the innermost gimbal to have an orientation remaining independent of the orientation, in space, of its support.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] In the case of a gyroscope with two gimbals, the outer gimbal, which is the gyroscope frame, is mounted so as to pivot about an axis in its own plane determined by the support.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] This outer gimbal possesses one degree of rotational freedom and its axis possesses none.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The second (inner) gimbal is mounted in the gyroscope frame (outer gimbal) so as to pivot about an axis in its own plane that is always perpendicular to the pivotal axis of the gyroscope frame (outer gimbal).
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] This inner gimbal has two degrees of rotational freedom.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The axle of the spinning wheel (the rotor) defines the spin axis.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The rotor is constrained to spin about an axis, which is always perpendicular to the axis of the inner gimbal.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] So the rotor possesses three degrees of rotational freedom and its axis possesses two.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The rotor responds to a force applied to the input axis by a reaction force to the output axis.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] A gyroscope flywheel will roll or resist about the output axis depending upon whether the output gimbals are of a free or fixed configuration.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] An example of some free-output-gimbal devices is the attitude control gyroscopes used to sense or measure the pitch, roll and yaw attitude angles in a spacecraft or aircraft.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The centre of gravity of the rotor can be in a fixed position.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The rotor simultaneously spins about one axis and is capable of oscillating about the two other axes, and it is free to turn in any direction about the fixed point (except for its inherent resistance caused by rotor spin).
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Some gyroscopes have mechanical equivalents substituted for one or more of the elements.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] For example, the spinning rotor may be suspended in a fluid, instead of being mounted in gimbals.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] A control moment gyroscope (CMG) is an example of a fixed-output-gimbal device that is used on spacecraft to hold or maintain a desired attitude angle or pointing direction using the gyroscopic resistance force.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] In some special cases, the outer gimbal (or its equivalent) may be omitted so that the rotor has only two degrees of freedom.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] In other cases, the centre of gravity of the rotor may be offset from the axis of oscillation, and thus the centre of gravity of the rotor and the centre of suspension of the rotor may not coincide.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Essentially, a gyroscope is a top combined with a pair of gimbals.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Tops were invented in many different civilizations, including classical Greece, Rome, and China.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Most of these were not utilized as instruments.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The first known apparatus similar to a gyroscope (the "Whirling Speculum" or "Serson's Speculum") was invented by John Serson in 1743.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] It was used as a level, to locate the horizon in foggy or misty conditions.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The first instrument used more like an actual gyroscope was made by Johann Bohnenberger of Germany, who first wrote about it in 1817.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Bohnenberger's machine was based on a rotating massive sphere.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Johnson developed a similar device that was based on a rotating disc.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The French mathematician Pierre-Simon Laplace, working at the École Polytechnique in Paris, recommended the machine for use as a teaching aid, and thus it came to the attention of Léon Foucault.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] In 1852, Foucault used it in an experiment demonstrating the rotation of the Earth.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] It was Foucault who gave the device its modern name, in an experiment to see (Greek *skopeein* 'to see') the Earth's rotation (Greek *gyros* 'circle, rotation'), which was visible in the 8 to 10 minutes before friction slowed the spinning rotor.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] In the 1860s, the advent of electric motors made it possible for a gyroscope to spin indefinitely; this led to the first prototype heading indicators, and a rather more complicated device, the gyrocompass.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The first functional gyrocompass was patented in 1904 by German inventor Hermann Anschütz-Kaempfe.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] American Elmer Sperry followed with his own design later that year, and other nations soon realized the military importance of the invention—in an age in which naval prowess was the most significant measure of military power—and created their own gyroscope industries.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The Sperry Gyroscope Company quickly expanded to provide aircraft and naval stabilizers as well, and other gyroscope developers followed suit.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Hurst Mfg Co of Indianapolis started producing the "Hurst gyroscope" a toy gyroscope with a pull string and pedestal.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Manufacture was at some point switched to Chandler Mfg Co (still branded Hurst).
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The product was later renamed to a "Chandler gyroscope", presumably because Chandler Mfg Co. took over rights to the gyroscope.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Chandler continued to produce the toy until the company was purchased by TEDCO Inc. in 1982.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The gyroscope is still produced by TEDCO today.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Similar principles were later employed in the development of inertial navigation systems for ballistic missiles.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] During World War II, the gyroscope became the prime component for aircraft and anti-aircraft gun sights.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] After the war, the race to miniaturize gyroscopes for guided missiles and weapons navigation systems resulted in the development and manufacturing of so-called **midget gyroscopes** that weighed less than 3 ounces (85 g) and had a diameter of approximately 1 inch (2.5 cm).
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Some of these miniaturized gyroscopes could reach a speed of 24,000 revolutions per minute in less than 10 seconds.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Gyroscopes continue to be an engineering challenge.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] For example, the axle bearings have to be extremely accurate.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] A small amount of friction is deliberately introduced to the bearings, since otherwise an accuracy of better than $10^{-7}$ of an inch (2.5 nm) would be required.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Three-axis MEMS-based gyroscopes are also used in portable electronic devices such as tablets, smartphones, and smartwatches.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] This adds to the 3-axis acceleration sensing ability available on previous generations of devices.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Together these sensors provide 6 component motion sensing; accelerometers for X, Y, and Z movement, and gyroscopes for measuring the extent and rate of rotation in space (roll, pitch and yaw).
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Some devices additionally incorporate a magnetometer to provide absolute angular measurements relative to the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Newer MEMS-based inertial measurement units incorporate up to all nine axes of sensing in a single integrated circuit package, providing inexpensive and widely available motion sensing.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] All spinning objects have gyroscopic properties.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The main properties that an object can experience in any gyroscopic motion are rigidity in space and precession.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Rigidity in space describes the principle that a gyroscope remains in the fixed position on the plane in which it is spinning, unaffected by the Earth's rotation. such as with a rotating bike wheel.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Early forms of gyroscope (not then known by the name) were used to demonstrate the principle.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] where $\phi '$ represents precession, $\psi '$ is represented by spin, $\theta$ is the nutation angle, and I represents inertia along its respective axis.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] This relation is only valid when the moments along the Y and Z axes are equal to 0.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The equation can be further reduced noting that the angular velocity along the z-axis is equal to the sum of the precession and the spin: $\omega _{z}=\phi '\cos \theta +\psi '$ , Where $\omega _{z}$ represents the angular velocity along the z axis.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Gyroscopic precession is torque induced.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] It is the rate of change of the angular momentum that is produced by the applied torque.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Precession produces counterintuitive dynamic results such as a spinning top not falling over.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Precession is used in aerospace applications for sensing changes of attitude and direction.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] A Steadicam rig was employed during the filming of the 1983 film *Return of the Jedi*, in conjunction with two gyroscopes for extra stabilization, to film the background plates for the speeder bike chase.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Steadicam inventor Garrett Brown operated the shot, walking through a redwood forest, running the camera at one frame per second.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] When projected at 24 frames per second, it gave the impression of flying through the air at perilous speeds.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The heading indicator or directional gyro has an axis of rotation that is set horizontally, pointing north.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Unlike a magnetic compass, it does not seek north.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] When being used in an airplane, for example, it will slowly drift away from north and will need to be reoriented periodically, using a magnetic compass as a reference.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Unlike a directional gyro or heading indicator, a gyrocompass seeks north.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] It detects the rotation of the Earth about its axis and seeks the *true* north, rather than the *magnetic* north.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Gyrocompasses usually have built-in damping to prevent overshoot when re-calibrating from sudden movement.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] By determining an object's acceleration and integrating over time, the velocity of the object can be calculated.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Integrating again, position can be determined.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The simplest accelerometer is a weight that is free to move horizontally, which is attached to a spring and a device to measure the tension in the spring.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] This can be improved by introducing a counteracting force to push the weight back and to measure the force needed to prevent the weight from moving.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] A more complicated design consists of a gyroscope with a weight on one of the axes.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The device will react to the force generated by the weight when it is accelerated, by integrating that force to produce a velocity.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] A **gyrostat** consists of a massive flywheel concealed in a solid casing.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Its behaviour on a table, or with various modes of suspension or support, serves to illustrate the curious reversal of the ordinary laws of static equilibrium due to the gyrostatic behaviour of the interior invisible flywheel when rotated rapidly.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The first gyrostat was designed by Lord Kelvin to illustrate the more complicated state of motion of a spinning body when free to wander about on a horizontal plane, like a top spun on the pavement, or a bicycle on the road.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Kelvin also made use of gyrostats to develop mechanical theories of the elasticity of matter and of the ether.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] In modern continuum mechanics there is a variety of these models, based on ideas of Lord Kelvin.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] They represent a specific type of Cosserat theories (suggested for the first time by Eugène Cosserat and François Cosserat), which can be used for description of artificially made smart materials as well as of other complex media.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] One of them, so-called Kelvin's medium, has the same equations as magnetic insulators near the state of magnetic saturation in the approximation of quasimagnetostatics.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] In modern times, the gyrostat concept is used in the design of attitude control systems for orbiting spacecraft and satellites.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] For instance, the Mir space station had three pairs of internally mounted flywheels known as *gyrodynes* or control moment gyroscopes.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] In physics, there are several systems whose dynamical equations resemble the equations of motion of a gyrostat.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] A microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) gyroscope is a miniaturized gyroscope found in electronic devices.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] It takes the idea of the Foucault pendulum and uses a vibrating element.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] This kind of gyroscope was first used in military applications but has since been adopted for increasing commercial use.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The hemispherical resonator gyroscope (HRG), also called a wine-glass gyroscope or mushroom gyro, makes use of a thin solid-state hemispherical shell, anchored by a thick stem.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] This shell is driven to a flexural resonance by electrostatic forces generated by electrodes which are deposited directly onto separate fused-quartz structures that surround the shell.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Gyroscopic effect is obtained from the inertial property of the flexural standing waves.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] A vibrating structure gyroscope (VSG), also called a Coriolis vibratory gyroscope (CVG), uses a resonator made of different metallic alloys.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] It takes a position between the low-accuracy, low-cost MEMS gyroscope and the higher-accuracy and higher-cost fiber optic gyroscope.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Accuracy parameters are increased by using low-intrinsic damping materials, resonator vacuumization, and digital electronics to reduce temperature dependent drift and instability of control signals.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] High quality wine-glass resonators are used for precise sensors like HRG.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] A dynamically tuned gyroscope (DTG) is a rotor suspended by a universal joint with flexure pivots.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The flexure spring stiffness is independent of spin rate.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] However, the dynamic inertia (from the gyroscopic reaction effect) from the gimbal provides negative spring stiffness proportional to the square of the spin speed (Howe and Savet, 1964; Lawrence, 1998).
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Therefore, at a particular speed, called the tuning speed, the two moments cancel each other, freeing the rotor from torque, a necessary condition for an ideal gyroscope.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] A ring laser gyroscope relies on the Sagnac effect to measure rotation by measuring the shifting interference pattern of a beam split into two separate beams which travel around the ring in opposite directions.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] When the Boeing 757-200 entered service in 1983, it was equipped with the first suitable ring laser gyroscope.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] This gyroscope took many years to develop, and the experimental models went through many changes before it was deemed ready for production by the engineers and managers of Honeywell and Boeing.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] It was an outcome of the competition with mechanical gyroscopes, which kept improving.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The reason Honeywell, of all companies, chose to develop the laser gyro was that they were the only one that did not have a successful line of mechanical gyroscopes, so they would not be competing against themselves.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The first problem they had to solve was that with laser gyros rotations below a certain minimum could not be detected at all, due to a problem called "lock-in", whereby the two beams act like coupled oscillators and pull each other's frequencies toward convergence and therefore zero output.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The solution was to shake the gyro rapidly so that it never settled into lock-in.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Paradoxically, too regular of a dithering motion produced an accumulation of short periods of lock-in when the device was at rest at the extremities of its shaking motion.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] This was cured by applying a random white noise to the vibration.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The material of the block was also changed from quartz to a new glass ceramic Cer-Vit, made by Owens Corning, because of helium leaks.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] A fiber optic gyroscope also uses the interference of light to detect mechanical rotation.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The two-halves of the split beam travel in opposite directions in a coil of fiber optic cable as long as 5 km.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Like the ring laser gyroscope, it makes use of the Sagnac effect.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] A London moment gyroscope relies on the quantum-mechanical phenomenon, whereby a spinning superconductor generates a magnetic field whose axis lines up exactly with the spin axis of the gyroscopic rotor.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] A magnetometer determines the orientation of the generated field, which is interpolated to determine the axis of rotation.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Gyroscopes of this type can be extremely accurate and stable.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] For example, those used in the Gravity Probe B experiment measured changes in gyroscope spin axis orientation to better than 0.5 milliarcseconds (1.4×10−7 degrees, or about 2.4×10−9 radians) over a one-year period.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] This is equivalent to an angular separation the width of a human hair viewed from 32 kilometers (20 mi) away.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The GP-B gyro consists of a nearly-perfect spherical rotating mass made of fused quartz, which provides a dielectric support for a thin layer of niobium superconducting material.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] To eliminate friction found in conventional bearings, the rotor assembly is centered by the electric field from six electrodes.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] After the initial spin-up by a jet of helium which brings the rotor to 4,000 RPM, the polished gyroscope housing is evacuated to an ultra-high vacuum to further reduce drag on the rotor.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Provided the suspension electronics remain powered, the extreme rotational symmetry, lack of friction, and low drag will allow the angular momentum of the rotor to keep it spinning for about 15,000 years.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] A sensitive DC SQUID that can discriminate changes as small as one quantum, or about 2 ×10−15 Wb, is used to monitor the gyroscope.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] A precession, or tilt, in the orientation of the rotor causes the London moment magnetic field to shift relative to the housing.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The moving field passes through a superconducting pickup loop fixed to the housing, inducing a small electric current.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The current produces a voltage across a shunt resistance, which is resolved to spherical coordinates by a microprocessor.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The system is designed to minimize Lorentz torque on the rotor.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The main rotor of a helicopter acts like a gyroscope.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Its motion is influenced by the principle of gyroscopic precession which is the concept that a force applied to a spinning object will have a maximum reaction approximately 90 degrees later.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The reaction may differ from 90 degrees when other stronger forces are in play.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] To change direction, helicopters must adjust the pitch angle and the angle of attack.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Gyro X prototype vehicle created by Alex Tremulis and Thomas Summers in 1967.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The car utilized gyroscopic precession to drive on two wheels.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] An assembly consisting of a flywheel mounted in a gimbal housing under the hood of the vehicle acted as a large gyroscope.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The flywheel was rotated by hydraulic pumps creating a gyroscopic effect on the vehicle.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] A precessional ram was responsible for rotating the gyroscope to change the direction of the precessional force to counteract any forces causing the vehicle imbalance.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The one-of-a-kind prototype is now at the Lane Motor Museum in Nashville, Tennessee.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] In addition to being used in compasses, aircraft, computer pointing devices, etc., gyroscopes have been introduced into consumer electronics.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Since the gyroscope allows the calculation of orientation and rotation, designers have incorporated them into modern technology.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] The integration of the gyroscope has allowed for more accurate recognition of movement within a 3D space than the previous lone accelerometer within a number of smartphones.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Gyroscopes in consumer electronics are frequently combined with accelerometers for more robust direction- and motion-sensing.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Examples of such applications include smartphones such as the Samsung Galaxy Note 4, HTC Titan, Nexus 5, iPhone 5s, Nokia 808 PureView and Sony Xperia, game console peripherals such as the PlayStation 3 controller and the Wii Remote, and virtual reality headsets such as the Oculus Rift.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Some features of Android phones like PhotoSphere or 360 Camera and to use VR gadget do not work without a gyroscope sensor in the phone.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Nintendo has integrated a gyroscope into the Wii console's Wii Remote controller by an additional piece of hardware called "Wii MotionPlus".
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] It is also included in the 3DS, Wii U GamePad, and Nintendo Switch Joy-Con and Pro controllers, which detect movement when turning and shaking.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] Cruise ships use gyroscopes to level motion-sensitive devices such as self-leveling pool tables.
[src:device-orientation/gyroscope] An electric powered flywheel gyroscope inserted in a bicycle wheel is sold as an alternative to training wheels.
